03904nam a22005535i 9789815011449DE-B159720240306015011.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022si     fo  d z      eng d  a97898150114497 a10.1355/97898150114492doi  a(DE-B1597)652372  a(OCoLC)1302012929  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  asicSG 7aPOL0290002bisacsh1 aDien, Nguyen An Luong, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA Study of Vietnam’s Control over Online Anti-state Content /cNguyen An Luong Dien. 1aSingapore : bISEAS Publishing, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (27 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tFOREWORD -- tEXECUTIVE SUMMARY -- tINTRODUCTION -- tREGULATING CONTENT -- tPORNOGRAPHY AS PRETEXT -- tFOLLOW IN CHINA’S FOOTSTEPS -- tSOCIAL MEDIA-GOVERNMENT RELATIONS: FROM ANIMOSITY TO ALLIANCE -- tPIVOT TO CO-OPTATION -- tTHE BLOOM IS OFF THE ROSE, BUT FACEBOOK IS HERE TO STAY -- tTHE ONLINE TUG-OF-WAR CONTINUES0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the past two decades, the fixation on anti-state content has shaped the way Vietnamese authorities deployed various censorship strategies to achieve the dual goals of creating a superficial openness while maintaining a tight grip on online discourses. These considerations dictated how several regulations on Internet controls were formulated and enforced. Vietnamese censors also selectively borrowed from China’s online censorship playbook, a key tenet of which is the fear-based approach. The modus operandi for the authorities is to first harp on what they perceive as online foreign and domestic threats to Vietnam’s social stability. Then those threats are exhaustively used to enforce tougher measures that are akin to those implemented in China. But unlike China, Vietnam has not afforded to ban Western social media platforms altogether. Realizing that they would be better off exploiting social media for their own gains, Vietnamese authorities have sought to co-opt and utilize it to curb anti-state content on the Internet. The lure of the Vietnamese market has also emboldened Facebook and Google’s YouTube to consider it fit to acquiesce to state censorship demands. The crackdown on anti-state content and fear-based censorship are likely to continue shaping Vietnam’s Internet controls, at least in the foreseeable future. The question is how both Internet users and the authorities will make the most of their unlikely—and fickle—alliance with social media to fulfil their agendas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aPublic Policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / Social Policy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076711740uhttps://doi.org/10.1355/978981501144940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9789815011449423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9789815011449/original  a978-3-11-076711-7  ISEAS Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles